Hence, We need to find an academic research article to summarise and write for our report. 12:53:54 - [name1] : Here are some general differences btw some practitioner and academic article just FYI 12:53:57 - [name1] :

In accounting, practitioner articles are typically written by professionals working in the field, such as practicing accountants or financial advisors, and are often focused on practical issues or solutions related to accounting and finance. These articles may provide practical advice, case studies, or real-world examples of how accounting principles are applied in practice.

Academic articles, on the other hand, are written by scholars or researchers and are often focused on theoretical or conceptual issues related to accounting and finance. These articles may include empirical studies, theoretical frameworks, or conceptual models that help to advance our understanding of accounting concepts and practices.

Some key differences between practitioner and academic articles in accounting may include:

  • Focus: Practitioner articles are typically focused on practical issues or solutions related to accounting and finance, while academic articles may be more theoretical or conceptual in nature.
  • Tone: Practitioner articles may be written in a more informal or accessible style, while academic articles may be more technical or specialized.
  • Sources: Practitioner articles may draw on practical experience or case studies, while academic articles may rely more heavily on empirical research or theoretical frameworks.
  • Audience: Practitioner articles are typically written for a professional audience, such as practicing accountants or financial advisors, while academic articles are aimed at an academic audience, such as researchers or scholars in the field of accounting.

Appendices include supplemental materials that may not be essential during the reading of a paper, but provide additional information for the reader. Appendices go at the end of the document after the reference list.

Formatting notes:

  • If there is one Appendix, label it as "Appendix." If there are two or more, label them each with a capital letter (e.g. Appendix A, Appendix B).
  • Each appendix should have atitle that describes its contents.
  • The appendix label and title should be in bold,centered and in title case at the top of the page where the appendix begins. The label and title should be on separate lines.
  • Each appendix should start on a new page.
  • Appendices can include text, figures, tables, etc., or a combination of related information in different formats.
  • If there is only one figure or table in an appendix, then the appendix label and title takethe place of the normal figure or table formatting.
  • For appendices with more than one figure or table, the figures and tables are formatted as described above. The numbering, however,would include a letter. For instance, Figure B3, is the third figure in Appendix B.
  • As with tables and figures, each appendix should be referred to in the text at the appropriate time (e.g. "see Appendix A").
